{"tool":"propose","gene_genome":{"mechanism_genome":"Use a partitioned or monolithic ALE-FSI formulation on time slabs I_n=(t_n,t_{n+1}], with fluid domain Ω_f(t), structure domain Ω_s, and interface Γ(t). For each candidate step Δt_n, compute a local estimator η_n^2 = η_{f,n}^2 + η_{s,n}^2 + η_{Γ,n}^2 + η_{geom,n}^2. Here η_{f,n} is a fluid residual indicator measuring the time-discrete Navier–Stokes/ALE momentum and incompressibility defects, including ALE convective defect ∂_t u_f|_χ + ((u_f-w)·∇)u_f. η_{s,n} is the structural residual from the chosen elastodynamic or elastostatic time integrator. η_{Γ,n} measures coupling defects: velocity/kinematic mismatch ||u_f - ∂_t d_s|| on Γ_n and traction-balance mismatch ||σ_f n_f + σ_s n_s||. η_{geom,n} measures moving-interface geometry error, e.g. the discrepancy between the predicted interface Γ_h^{pred}(t) and a reconstructed higher-order interface Γ_h^{rec}(t), plus violations of the discrete geometric conservation law J_t - J ∇·w = 0 in the ALE map. Accept Δt_n if η_n ≤ TOL_n and update Δt_{n+1}=ρ Δt_n (TOL_n/η_n)^{1/(p+1)}, with safety factor ρ and temporal order p.","niche_genome":"Coupled incompressible-fluid/elastic-structure simulations with large or moderate interface motion, especially ALE finite-element, isogeometric, cut-cell, or immersed-interface discretizations where time-step failure may arise either from PDE temporal truncation error or from inaccurate representation of Γ(t).","observation_genome":"In moving-interface FSI, a small PDE residual does not guarantee accuracy if the interface trajectory, normal vector, Jacobian, or ALE mesh velocity is geometrically under-resolved. Conversely, a conservative time step chosen only from interface displacement may be unnecessarily small when the PDE residual is dominant. Separating η_{geom,n} from η_{f,n}, η_{s,n}, and η_{Γ,n} makes the time-step controller diagnostic: it can reduce Δt, increase interface reconstruction order, remesh, or improve coupling iterations depending on which term dominates.","limitation_genome":"The proposed estimator requires computable reconstructions of the interface trajectory and ALE map, and constants in the reliability/efficiency bounds may depend on mesh quality, density ratio, added-mass effects, and nonlinear solver tolerances. For strongly added-mass-dominated regimes, partitioned schemes may require subiteration or implicit coupling before the residual indicators are meaningful.","delta_genome":"Compared with standard CFL-like or residual-only adaptive time stepping, the proposed method introduces an explicit geometric indicator based on interface reconstruction and discrete geometric conservation law defects. This distinguishes temporal PDE error from geometric motion error and coupling error on each time slab.","claim_genome":"A robust adaptive time-stepping strategy for moving-interface FSI should control a composite local indicator η_n with separate fluid, structure, interface-coupling, and geometry components. In particular, including η_{geom,n} is necessary for reliability whenever Γ(t) is approximated by a time-discrete ALE, cut, immersed, or projected interface representation, because geometric under-resolution can produce first-order consistency errors in mass conservation, traction transfer, and interface work balance even when the fluid and structure residuals are small."}}

